s in Fragile Conviction that ideational power must be understood in relation to three aspects: the voicing of the idea, its tension with everyday reality, and its reverberation within groups of listeners. The conclusion that the power of conviction is rooted in the instability of sociocultural contexts is a message that has relevance far beyond urban Central Asia.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIdeologyzKyrgyzstan. 0aIdeology. 0aIntellectual life. 0aPost-communismzKyrgyzstan. 0aPost-communism. 0aReligious life. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aReligious Studies.  asecular ideology, religious ideology, post-Soviet frontier, southern Kyrgyzstan, ethnography, Kyrgyz society, power of ideology, limitations of ideology, Soviet agitprop, Christian, Muslim, faith healers.2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501708381?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708381423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708381/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles